{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 MIDI Channel Matrix Router\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Purpose\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This simple plugin allows to modify the routing of MIDI channels with a simple matrix. Just tick the corresponding in -> out box to define a route between an input channel and an output channel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It also adds conditional options on the MIDI event type, and the MIDI bus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Split\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you want to split a channel to multiple routes, just check multiple boxes on a line.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ##\u160?Firewall\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If no boxes match the input channel (the complete line for an input channel is unchecked), then corresponding events are simply dropped.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Channel Pass through\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you want to pass through an original event for channel x, just check the x/x box.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 MIDI Bus handling\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A basic handling of MIDI Buses is offered : the plugin will only handle events from the "In" MIDI Bus, other buses are left untouched. You may set it to "ANY" to handle all MIDI Buses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may also reroute the input MIDI Bus(es) to another one by changing the "Out" MIDI Bus. If you do so, you can specifically check the "PT" (Passthrough) option to prevent the incoming events from being dropped from the original bus (this is a way to "fork" and modify the input bus(es)).\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
